<div class="usefulpage">
	<div class="row">
		<div class="column">
			<h1>Will the genetic test give me <strong>useful information</strong>?</h1>
			<p>The test for the gene related to Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease can detect if you have an increased chance of getting the disease, <strong>but it cannot predict for sure if you will get the disease</strong> &mdash;  <strong>or if you won&rsquo;t</strong>.</p>
			<h3>About Gene Tests</h3>
			<p>In general, genetic tests look for variations in genes that, when present, can lead to an illness or raise one&rsquo;s chances of developing an illness. Genetic tests are done on small amounts of saliva or blood or by swabbing the inside of the mouth.</p>
			<h3>Alzheimer&rsquo;s and the APOE&nbsp;Gene</h3>
			<p>Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease can be caused by genes, non-inherited factors, or some combination of both. There is one gene that has been associated with late-onset Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease. It is called the Apolipoprotein E gene â€“ or APOE for short.</p>
			<p>The APOE gene has three forms: e2, e3, and e4. The e4 form is the one which is associated with a higher risk of Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease. The genetic test can tell which form or forms of the gene are present. A person can have zero, one, or two copies of the e4 gene.</p>
			<p>If you have one copy of the e4 gene, the risk for developing Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease increases compared to other people and two copies makes the risk higher. Research is ongoing so we don&rsquo;t know the exact risk. The estimated risk is shown in the following figures.</p>
			<h3>Risk of Developing Alzheimer&rsquo;s disease</h3>
			<ul class="legend">
				<li class="legend-purple">
					The percentages and the purple parts of each bar indicate the chance of developing Alzheimer&rsquo;s by ages 65, 75 and 85 based on the number of APOE e4 genes. 
				</li>
				<li class="legend-gray">
					The gray parts of each bar indicate the chance of not developing Alzheimer&rsquo;s.
				</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
	</div>
